To generate a table of contents automatically in a LaTeX document, you need to include the `toc` command and use a `\tableofcontents` command. Also, ensure your document's sections (like chapters, sections, etc.) are defined with appropriate LaTeX section commands. Below is an example:

```latex
\documentclass{book}
\usepackage{lipsum} % for dummy text

% Set up the TOC structure with headings.
\newcommand{\sectionhead}[1]{\section{#1}}
\newcommand{\subsectionhead}[1]{\subsection{#1}}

\begin{document}

% Begin the Table of Contents
\tableofcontents

% Now, let's start writing the main content of our document.
\chapter{Introduction}
\lipsum[1]

\sectionhead{History of LaTeX}
\lipsum[2-5]

\subsectionhead{LaTeX vs. Other Document Preparation Systems}
\lipsum[6]

\sectionhead{Advantages of LaTeX}
\lipsum[7]

\subsectionhead{Customization}
\lipsum[8]

\subsectionhead{Consistency and Quality}
\lipsum[9]

\sectionhead{Conclusion}
\lipsum[10]

\end{document}
```

In this example:

- `\documentclass{book}`: This sets the document class to `book`, which is suitable for books and large documents. If your document is a paper, you might choose a different class like `article`.

- `\usepackage{lipsum}`: This package is used for inserting dummy text (Lorem Ipsum) so that the example will have readable content.

- `\newcommand{\sectionhead}[1]{\section{#1}}`: This defines a macro to create a section heading, which is useful if you want to avoid typing `\section{}` repeatedly.

- `\newcommand{\subsectionhead}[1]{\subsection{#1}}`: This defines a similar macro for subsections.

- `\tableofcontents`: This command generates the table of contents at the specified location.

- `\chapter`, `\section`, `\subsection`, and their respective commands (`\sectionhead`, `\subsectionhead`) are used to define headers throughout the document. The text within these headers is used to populate the table of contents. 

When you compile this LaTeX file, the table of contents will be generated automatically. Each time you add a new section or subsection, the table of contents updates to reflect the changes.

